<li id="cite_note-74"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-74">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFGibb1969" class="citation book cs1">Gibb, Sir Hamilton (1969). <i>Mohammedanism: an historical survey</i>. Oxford University Press. p.&#160;1. <q>Modern Muslims dislike the terms Mohammedan and Mohammedanism, which seem to them to carry the implication of worship of Mohammed, as Christian and Christianity imply the worship of Christ.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mohammedanism%3A+an+historical+survey&amp;rft.pages=1&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1969&amp;rft.aulast=Gibb&amp;rft.aufirst=Sir+Hamilton&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMuslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
